## What is this pull request?
Bindings of Iroha crypto for Python and Java
   
## Why do you implement it? Why do we need this pull request?
Iroha uses custom signature algorithm (ed25519 with sha-3 inside) so we need support it for different languages. Bindings are the easiest way.
  
## How to use the features provided in the pull request?
Bindings libraries are disabled by default. To generate them add ```-DSWIG=ON``` option to your cmake command, e. g. (if you are in build/ directory):
```cmake -DSWIG=ON ..```
Now you can build Iroha as usual. After the build process is completed navigate to ```build/shared_model/cryptography/ed25519_sha3_impl/bindings/```. You can use Iroha crypto from Python in a next way:
```
import irohacrypto
blob1 = irohacrypto.Blob("1")
blob2 = irohacrypto.Blob("2")
prov = irohacrypto.CryptoProvider()
keypair = prov.generateKeypair()
sig = prov.sign(blob1, keypair)
print(prov.verify(sig, blob1, keypair.publicKey()))
print(prov.verify(sig, blob2, keypair.publicKey()))
```
And from Java:
```
public class my {
  static {
    try {
        System.loadLibrary("irohacrypto");
    } catch (UnsatisfiedLinkError e) {
      System.err.println("Native code library failed to load. \n" + e);
      System.exit(1);
    }
  }

  public static void main(String argv[]) {
    Blob blob1 = new Blob("1");
    Blob blob2 = new Blob("2");
    CryptoProvider prov = new CryptoProvider();
    Keypair keypair = prov.generateKeypair();
    Signed sig = prov.sign(blob1, keypair);
    System.out.println(prov.verify(sig, blob1, keypair.publicKey()));
    System.out.println(prov.verify(sig, blob2, keypair.publicKey()));
  }
}
```
and then run
```
javac *.java
```
If everything has gone well you will receive the next result:
```
true
false
```
Also please note that shared object library for Python (_irohacrypto.so) is different from Java library (libirohacrypto.so) even though they provide exactly the same functionality.

**Note about Java:** if you run your Java code you've just built you will probably give the ```java.lang.UnsatisfiedLinkError``` exception. The reason is because Java runtime can't find native .so library (libirohacrypto.so in our case). Just use the next command:
```
LD_LIBRARY_PATH=. java my
```
where **my** is a name of your manually created file.

