This PR adds Rust-like `result<V, E>` type, which can be used instead of `optional<V>`.
This type is either `V` (value) or `E` (error). 

Pattern matching and monads can be used with this type:
```C++
using R = iroha::result<int, std::string>;

R increment_but_less_5(int a) {
  if (a < 5) {
    return Ok(a + 1);
  } else {
    return Error(":("s);
  }
}

TEST(Result, monadic) {
  R a = 1;
  ASSERT_TRUE(a);

  R b = a | increment_but_less_5 | increment_but_less_5;

  ASSERT_TRUE(a);
  ASSERT_TRUE(b);
  ASSERT_EQ(*b, *a + 2);

  R c = b | increment_but_less_5 | increment_but_less_5 | increment_but_less_5;
  ASSERT_FALSE(c);
  ASSERT_EQ(c.error(), ":("s);
}

TEST(Result, pattern_matching) {
  R a = 1;
  ASSERT_TRUE(a);

  // in one order
  a.match<void>([](Ok_t<int> const& v)            { SUCCEED(); },
                [](Error_t<std::string> const& e) { FAIL();    });

  // in reversed order
  a.match<void>([](Error_t<std::string> const & e) { FAIL();    },
                [](Ok_t<int> const& v)             { SUCCEED(); });

  int k = 
  a.match<int>([](Error_t<std::string> const& e) { return 1; },
               [](Ok_t<int> const& v)            { return 2; });
 
  ASSERT_EQ(k, 2); // true, because a holds int (value)
  
}

```

`result<V, E>` is useful instead of optional in sequential tasks, such as deserialization of fields in JSON/protobuf.

## What is this pull request?
Async Torii service implementation.

## How to use the features provided in the pull request?
### Example
If we want to deal multiple rpc in a service, we can do such as follows:
```proto
service Service {
  rpc SendTx(Tx) returns TxResponse
  rpc SendQuery(Query) returns QueryResponse
}
```
```cpp
class ServiceHandler : public GrpcAsyncService {
public:
  void handleRpcs() {
    // Spawn a new request state manager.
    enqueueRequest<Tx, TxResponse>(
      &Service::AsyncService::RequestSendTx, // specify auto created request method
      &ServiceHandler::SendTxHandler              // handler function
    );
    enqueueRequest<Query, QueryResponse>(
      &Service::AsyncService::RequestSendQuery,
      &ServiceHandler::SendQueryHandler
    );
    ...
  }

public:
  template <class RequestType, class ResponseType>
  using ServiceCall = Call<ServiceHandler, Service::AsyncService, RequestType, ResponseType>;

private:
  void SendTxHandler(ServiceCall<Tx, TxResponse>* call) {
    // Inject request and response from call object
    auto request = call->request();
    auto& response = call->response();

    Service::SendTx(request, &response);  // call actual `SendTx()` If we extract this function to outside, we can deal async rpc easily like sync serives.

    enqueueRequest<Tx, TxResponse>(...);  // Re-spawn a new request state manager. Current one will be auto deleted.
  }

  void SendQueryHandler(ServiceCall<Query, QueryResponse>* call) {
    ...
    enqueueRequest<Query, QueryResponse>(...);
  }
}
```

- One `Call` instance manages one async rpc call. It manages rpc state and executes actual procedures.

